Stellt euch eine sehr lange Webseite mit einer Menge Abschnitten vor (also eine HTML-Spezifikation auf einer Seite). Wenn der Nutzer einen bestimmten Abschnitt anfordert (z. B. page.html#section7), wie wäre es, wenn der Webserver diesen Abschnitt zuerst streamt und danach die anderen Abschnitte?
Streamreihenfolge:
1. Beginn des HTML-Dokuments bis
2. HTML für Abschnitt 7
3. HTML für Abschnitt 1, 2, 3 usw.
Then the browser would ensure that sections 1 to 6 are displayed *over* section 7 on the web page.
Does that make sense? Would that be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible without having to implement additional elements with JavaScript. I simply want an extra-long HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered quickly. HTML should be able to handle this.
The content could be streamed, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
It would not be streamed in order, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it had been streamed in order.
@user22 You can also reorder documents without JS. You should not use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters so the server knows which section you want first. When reordering the sections, you have several options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use a template with sections
@user23 Yes. The issue is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML function that allows streaming out of order, but still arranges the content in the DOM order for the browser.
But the idea with the slots looks promising. I'll give it a try.
@user22 Oh, do you want the browser to sort out the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first just so the user can see it as quickly as possible. If this could be done without affecting the DOM order, that would be good, then the browser would ensure that the resulting DOM order matches the visual order.
So, Section 7 should be streamed first, but the final result should look as if all sections were streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Check out PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
